Install Apache Airflow on Windows (Without Docker) – Step-by-Step Guide (2026)
This guide explains how to install Apache Airflow on Windows using WSL (Ubuntu) without Docker.
Airflow runs best on Linux, so we install it using Ubuntu via Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL).

📺 Reference Video:
https://youtu.be/mUA9k2N-Ros

Prerequisites:
Before starting, ensure you have:
Windows 10 or Windows 11
Microsoft Store access
Internet connection
Basic terminal knowledge

Step 1 — Install Ubuntu (WSL)
Open Microsoft Store
Search for Ubuntu
Install the Ubuntu Terminal App

After installation:
Launch Ubuntu
The first launch will ask you to:
Create a username
Create a password
Example:
Username: gospel
Password: ********
Once completed, you will have a Linux terminal running on Windows.

Step 2 — Check Airflow Compatibility
Before installing Airflow, always check the official PyPI page:
🔗 https://pypi.org/project/apache-airflow/
This page shows:
Latest Airflow version
Supported Python versions
⚠️ Airflow versions change frequently, so always verify compatibility.
For this guide we use:
AIRFLOW_VERSION=3.1.8
PYTHON_VERSION=3.12

Step 3 — Update Ubuntu Packages
Update system packages before installing dependencies:
type the following in your terminal:
- AIRFLOW_VERSION=3.1.8
- PYTHON_VERSION=3.12
- sudo apt update
Enter your password if prompted.

Step 4 — Install Python and Required Dependencies
Install the required Python version and development packages:
- sudo apt install -y python3.12 python3.12-venv python3.12-dev python3-pip build-essential

Step 5 — Create a Python Virtual Environment
Create a virtual environment for Airflow:
- mkdir -p ~/venvs
- python${PYTHON_VERSION} -m venv ~/venvs/airflow_${AIRFLOW_VERSION}

Activate the environment:
- source ~/venvs/airflow_${AIRFLOW_VERSION}/bin/activate
Your terminal should now look like:
(airflow_3.1.8) user@machine:~$

Step 6 — Upgrade pip
Upgrade pip to the latest version.
- pip install --upgrade pip

Step 7 — Install Apache Airflow
Define the constraints file.
This ensures compatible dependency versions are installed:
- CONSTRAINT_URL="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/apache/airflow/constraints-${AIRFLOW_VERSION}/constraints-${PYTHON_VERSION}.txt"
Install Airflow:
- pip install "apache-airflow==${AIRFLOW_VERSION}" --constraint "$CONSTRAINT_URL"

Step 8 — Start Airflow
To start Airflow,open new ubuntu terminal, activate the environment and run:
- source ~/venvs/airflow_${AIRFLOW_VERSION}/bin/activate
- airflow standalone

⚠️ Important:
Keep this terminal running
Do not close the terminal while Airflow is active

Airflow will start:
Scheduler
Webserver
Metadata database

Step 9 — Access the Airflow Web UI
Open your browser and navigate to:
http://localhost:8080
Login with:
Username: admin
Password: (generated by Airflow)
The password is displayed in the terminal logs during startup.
You can also find it in:
simple_auth_manager_passwords.json.generated

Step 10 — Open the Airflow Project in VS Code
Open a new Ubuntu terminal and navigate to the Airflow directory.
cd airflow
code .
When VS Code opens:
Ensure the bottom-left shows WSL: Ubuntu
This confirms you are working inside the Linux environment.

Step 11 — in your vscode,Create Your First DAG
Create the dags folder if it does not exist.

-- mkdir -p dags

Create a new file:my_first_airflow_dag.py
paste the code below inthe file:
from airflow import DAG
from airflow.operators.bash import BashOperator
from datetime import datetime

with DAG(
    dag_id='my_first_airflow_dag',
    start_date=datetime(2025, 8, 1),
    schedule='@daily',
    catchup=False,
) as dag:
    start_task = BashOperator(
        task_id='start_task',
        bash_command='echo "Starting the workflow!"',
    )
    welcome_task = BashOperator(
        task_id='welcome_task',
        bash_command='echo "Welcome, $(whoami)! This is your first Airflow DAG."',
    )
    end_task = BashOperator(
        task_id='end_task',
        bash_command='echo "Workflow completed!"',
    )
    start_task >> welcome_task >> end_task

Step 12 — View the DAG in Airflow
Go to the Airflow Web UI
Search for: my_first_airflow_dag
Enable the DAG
Trigger it manually if needed.
You should now see your first Airflow workflow running.

Project Structure
Typical Airflow directory structure:

airflow/
│
├── dags/
│   └── my_first_airflow_dag.py
│
├── logs/
├── plugins/
└── airflow.cfg

Useful Commands
Activate Airflow environment: source ~/venvs/airflow_3.1.8/bin/activate
Start Airflow: airflow standalone
Stop Airflow: CTRL + C

Conclusion
You have successfully:
Installed Apache Airflow on Windows
